bution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a nickname from the Old French vocabulary word <i>amabel</i>, <i>amable</i> ‘lovely’ (akin to modern English <i>amiable</i> ‘friendly, good-humoured’). The initial vowel began to be lost as early as the 12th century (the same woman is referred to as both <i>Mabilia</i> and <i>Amabilia</i> in a document of  1185 ), but a short vowel in the resulting first syllable was standard, giving a rhyme with <i>babble</i>, until the 19th century, when people began to pronounce the name to rhyme with <i>table</i>."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705185,"age":9,"year":"1106","julianDay":2125018,"title":"The Battle of Tichebray","description":"King Henry I defeated and captured his brother, Robert of Normandy, at the Battle of Tinchebray in 1106. Robert remained in captivity until his death in 1134.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Mabel Soligny was born in 1097, in Bristol, Gloucestershire, England, her father, Philip de Soligny, was 33 and her mother, Hawis de Vernon, was 30. She had at least 1 son with Jordan Champernon. She died on 29 September 1157, in Évreux, Eure, Normandy, France, at the age of 60, and was buried in Orne, Normandy, France."},"et":{"1097–29 September 1157":"1097–29. september 1157","1097–1157":"1097–1157","1100–Male":"1100–Surnud","1096–1190":"1096–1190","1140–1190":"1140–1190","1064–1114":"1064–1114","1068–1145":"1068–1145","1190":"1190","1097":"1097","1064":"1064","1140":"1140","1096":"1096","1095":"1095","1106":"1106","1114":"1114","1157":"1157","1145":"1145","1068":"1068","1100":"1100","29 September 1157":"29. september 1157","Evreux, Eure, Haute-Normandie, France":"Évreux, Eure, Normandie, Prantsusmaa","Cambernon, Manche, Normandy, France":"Cambernon, Manche, Normandie, Prantsusmaa","Bristol, Gloucestershire, England":"Bristol, Gloucestershire, England","Devonshire, England":"Devon, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Glouceste